SURVO84ED 81 120    81 S20                                                       *SAVE EDQ08D                                                                     *LOAD EDQ                                                                        *                                                                                *FOOTNOTE?                                                                       *Footnotes can be written and placed to the end of the current page              *automatically as follows:                                                       *Indicate in the text the place that refers to the footnote by the               *character '*' with 'F' as the shadow character. In the final printing,          *this character will be replaced by the index of the footnote.                   *This line must be followed an empty line and the lines containing the           *footnote text. The footnote text is terminated by an empty line.                *                                                                                *Example:                                                                        S    This is text having references* to two footnotes.*                          *                                                                                * This is the first footnote text.                                               *                                                                                * This is the second footnote text                                               *taking two lines.                                                               *                                                                                *The text continues...                                                           *@C                                                                              *The control of the page changes is automatic. PRINT takes into account          *the lengths of the footnotes.                                                   *                                                                                *The reference numbers for footnotes are 1,2,3,... unless otherwise              *stated by [footnote_number(n)] where n will be the number of the                *next footnote. By using [footnote_number(1)] on header lines, counting          *will be reset for each page.                                                    *The typeface etc. for footnotes is controlled by control words                  *[NOTE_START] and [NOTE_END]. See the proper device driver for default           *settings.                                                                       *                                                                                *   P = More information on PRINT                                                % P=PRINT2?                                                                      *@SELECT                                                                         *                                                                                *INDEXPR?                                                                        *An automatic index with page numbers for selected keywords and phrases          *is initiated by the control line                                                *   - index <name_of_text_file> .                                                *The keywords must be indicated in the text either by putting a '*' as           *a shadow character to any place within a word or by indicating                  *the start of a (longer) keyphrase by the shadow '[' and the end                 *of it by the shadow ']'.                                                        *The keysucro S simplifies typing of such shadow characters.                     *The resulting text file containing the key words and their page numbers         *can be edited later. For example, it can be converted to a Survo                *data file (by FILE SAVE), sorted (by FILE SORT) and edited (by FILE SHOW).      *                                                                                *   P = More information on PRINT                                                % P=PRINT2?                                                                      *@SELECT                                                                         *                                                                                *ASCIITXT?                                                                       *The text in the PRINT list (without control characters and page                 *headers) can be saved in an ASCII text file by giving a control line            *   - ascii_text <name_of_text_file> .                                           *In this way, texts made in Survo can be transferred to other                    *systems.                                                                        *                                                                                *   P = More information on PRINT                                                % P=PRINT2?                                                                      *@SELECT                                                                         *                                                                                *PSMISC?                                                                         *Miscellaneous control lines in PRINT (for PostScript printing)                  *   A = - replace                                                                *   B = - def_space                                                              *   C = - silent                                                                C*   D = - list                                                                  C*   P = More information on PRINT                                                %A=PSREPL B=PSSPACE C=SILENT D=PRLIST P=PRINT2?                                  *@SELECT                                                                         *                                                                                *PRLIST?                                                                         *A control line (with a '-' in the control column) in the print list             *and having the form                                                             *  - list <LST_file>                                                             *specifies chapters defined in <LST_file> to be printed (as by - chapter).       *                                                                                *  L = LST files                                                                 *  P = More information on PRINT                                                 %L=DLIST? P=PRINT2?                                                              *                                                                                *PSREPL?                                                                         *   - replace <string1> <string2>                                                *as a control line in the PRINT list replaces each occurrence of                 *<string1> in the text to be printed by <string2>. Only the latest               *- replace line is valid.                                                        *This feature is useful in giving varying chapter names or numbers               *on header lines typically in the form                                           *   - replace ????? 3.1                                                          *@G MM                                                                           *                                                                                *PSSPACE?                                                                        *   - def_space <character>                                                      *replaces <character> by a space character on all - define and - shadow          *lines. Example:                                                                 *   - def_space _                                                                *@G MM                                                                           *                                                                                *SILENT?                                                                         *   - silent                                                                     *as a control line in the PRINT list cancels all temporary displays              *during the PRINT operation.                                                     *@G MM                                                                           *                                                                                *MM?                                                                             *                                                                                *   M = More information on miscellaneous control lines in PRINT                 *                                                                                %M=PSMISC                                                                        *                                                                                *                                                                                *                                                                                *                                                                                *                                                                                *                                                                                *                                                                                Shadows                                                                          ␀                                   F                  F                        END                                                                              